<div id="review_1599370161" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1599370161" />
    <a title="Kate" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/29383287-kate"><img alt="Kate" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1579560971p2/29383287.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1599370161?book_show_action=true">Apr 03, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kate" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kate" href="/user/show/29383287-kate">Kate</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780679767398" href="/book/show/33263.South_of_the_Border_West_of_the_Sun">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/29383287-kate?shelf=japanese-lit">japanese-lit</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/29383287-kate?shelf=murakami">murakami</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/29383287-kate?shelf=read-in-2020">read-in-2020</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/29383287-kate?shelf=read-in-2016">read-in-2016</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/29383287-kate?shelf=favorite-standalones">favorite-standalones</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1599370161" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11711351396805556894">Reread April 2020;<br/>5/5stars<br/><br/>I stand by this being my fave murakami contemporary. So relatable, so beautiful, so haunting. I love how much this differs from the “typical” murakami novel but also still is just as powerful.<br/><br/><br/>First read July 2016;<br/>4.5/5 stars<br/><br/>OKay, let&apos;s do this. This is my NINTH book I&apos;ve read from Haruki Murakami - so I&apos;m not going to talk about his writing and his style because obviously I absolutely adore it. I&apos;m going to just talk about THIS book by him.<br/><br/>This seemed to me like just a </span>
  <span id="freeText11711351396805556894" style="display:none">Reread April 2020;<br />5/5stars<br /><br />I stand by this being my fave murakami contemporary. So relatable, so beautiful, so haunting. I love how much this differs from the “typical” murakami novel but also still is just as powerful.<br /><br /><br />First read July 2016;<br />4.5/5 stars<br /><br />OKay, let's do this. This is my NINTH book I've read from Haruki Murakami - so I'm not going to talk about his writing and his style because obviously I absolutely adore it. I'm going to just talk about THIS book by him.<br /><br />This seemed to me like just a better version of Norwegian Wood. I wasn't the biggest fan of Norwegian Wood - yes, I know, unpopular opinion especially for a Murakami fan. But where that book lacked depth and emotion for me, this book soared. This book follows a man named Hajime who is an only child, and becomes best friends with a girl named Shimamoto. It chronicles their childhood friendship, getting torn away from each other when Hajime moves, and then his life up until thirty six years old when he is happily married with two little girls and running an extremely successful bar in Tokyo. <br /><br />First, let me say, I enjoyed this a lot because the character of Hajime differed SO much from our previous narrators. Excluding Hard Boiled Wonderland (because what on earth even was that book, seriously, it's so insanely different from all Murakami's books I almost always forget it was by him!) and Kafka, all of Murakami's narrators are extremely similar men with no idea where they're going, what they want to do in life, and basically all they do is read and have a cat before suddenly the universe takes them on a wild journey. Hajime was such a dynamic character. He was actually successful in his work, he had a successful marriage and children and also had varying hobbies and interests - it was just a very refreshing after reading like seven books about almost the exact same character.<br /><br />I also liked Shimamoto, Izumi and Yukiko - basically, the women in this novel were just so much more fleshed out and interesting and HUMAN than in his other novels. Most love interests in Murakami books are just very boring in my opinion, but these women were all, again, very dynamic and interesting. I loved how Murakami showed where Izumi was years after Hajime and her dated. I really loved how Shimamoto introduced that weird aspect of Murakami books that I love so much - mystery, strange characters with strange motives, and just a hint of magical realism. And Yukiko, thank the gods for Yukiko, this woman was so incredibly realistic, especially toward the end of the book. She was a woman who knew exactly what she wanted, she was realistic in what she asked of her husband, and eventually she actually had a heart and forgave him and I just really appreciated her.<br /><br />I also just enjoyed the plot and the twists and such, they just simply worked for me. Although this is very similar to most of Murakami's love stories, this one just worked better in my opinion. I loved the twist with Shimamoto, I loved the ending with Hajime and Yukiko and overall I just really enjoyed this book.<br /><br />The only problem I had with it was the length - it was just a bit too short and I felt left hanging a little bit. As well as I wish there had been a bit more magical realism to it since that is my favorite part of reading Murakami!</span>
  <a data-text-id="11711351396805556894" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


