    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_755657712" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/755657712" />
    <a title="Ms. Smartarse" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13703358-ms-smartarse"><img alt="Ms. Smartarse" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1401273675p2/13703358.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/755657712?book_show_action=true">Nov 03, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ms. Smartarse" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ms. Smartarse" href="/user/show/13703358-ms-smartarse">Ms. Smartarse</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 130x200 9789736816321" href="/book/show/3189286-la-sud-de-grani-la-vest-de-soare">review of another edition</a>

          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">people who're not too bothered by the (lack of) plot </span></div>

        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13703358-ms-smartarse?shelf=translated_into_romanian">translated_into_romanian</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13703358-ms-smartarse?shelf=japanese-lit">japanese-lit</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13703358-ms-smartarse?shelf=mid-xx-century">mid-xx-century</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13703358-ms-smartarse?shelf=slice-of-life">slice-of-life</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13703358-ms-smartarse?shelf=drama">drama</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer755657712" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3470370419604465990"><em>Published in English as <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/17799.South_of_the_Border__West_of_the_Sun' title='South of the Border, West of the Sun by Haruki Murakami' rel='nofollow noopener'>South of the Border, West of the Sun</a>.</em><br/><br/>Just out of college, I was suddenly overcome by this maddening desire to write, and do it <em>well</em>. So well, that everyone would want to read the things I wrote. As a matter of fact, I was so impressed with the idea, that I would tell everyone how a truly great writer could practically write about <em>SOCKS</em> and have a legion of followers.<br/><br/>... then I entered the &quot;adult world&quot; and realized that I had vastly overestimated my sock-story-reading-tim</span>
  <span id="freeText3470370419604465990" style="display:none"><em>Published in English as <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/17799.South_of_the_Border__West_of_the_Sun" title="South of the Border, West of the Sun by Haruki Murakami" rel="nofollow noopener">South of the Border, West of the Sun</a>.</em><br><br>Just out of college, I was suddenly overcome by this maddening desire to write, and do it <em>well</em>. So well, that everyone would want to read the things I wrote. As a matter of fact, I was so impressed with the idea, that I would tell everyone how a truly great writer could practically write about <em>SOCKS</em> and have a legion of followers.<br><br>... then I entered the "adult world" and realized that I had vastly overestimated my sock-story-reading-time.<br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1405708818ra/10440059.gif" alt="no time" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>What does all this have to do with <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/3354.Haruki_Murakami" title="Haruki Murakami" rel="nofollow noopener">Haruki Murakami</a>'s <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/17799.South_of_the_Border__West_of_the_Sun" title="South of the Border, West of the Sun by Haruki Murakami" rel="nofollow noopener">South of the Border west of the sun</a>? Why the socks, of course! And by "socks" I mean "love", that is to say "sex"... maybe both. Or quite possibly neither. And you know what? I loved it so much that I don't even care!<br><br>As I told my best friend, this is the story of a guy who was OK as a kid, and then he started to grow up into a jerk. When he became an adult he realized he was a jerk, but he still couldn't help being one... and then got (temporarily) depressed over it. For a while, after meeting his childhood best friend he became a sap, but that was really temporary and he eventually got back to being his usual (jerky) self. THE END.<br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1405708988ra/10440088.gif" width="350" alt="you're not perfect, but who cares?" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>Good thing I don't work in PR, or this book would have totally flopped. That said, I still can't really find anything better to say about its content, aside from having absolutely loved it. So yeah: socks!<br><br><strong>Score: 4/5 stars</strong><br><br>OK, so I didn't exactly love <em>everything</em> about it, hence the rating. The ending left me really confused, which is saying <em>something</em> given Murakami's tendency towards open-ended finales. Still this one was just... idungeddit.<br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1567882129ra/28115141.gif" alt="I don't get it" width="350" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>It kind of felt as if I were listening to an ex-classmate's drunken confessions during a high school reunion. Sort of sad, pathetic... and maybe even somewhat boring, but <em>dayum</em> do I wanna know how it all ends!</span>
  <a data-text-id="3470370419604465990" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


