  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2918178391" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2918178391" />
    <a title="Algernon (Darth Anyan)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4728718-algernon-darth-anyan"><img alt="Algernon (Darth Anyan)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1553101944p2/4728718.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2918178391?book_show_action=true">Aug 19, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Algernon (Darth Anyan)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Algernon (Darth Anyan)" href="/user/show/4728718-algernon-darth-anyan">Algernon (Darth Anyan)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780679767398" href="/book/show/33263.South_of_the_Border_West_of_the_Sun">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4728718-algernon-darth-anyan?shelf=2019">2019</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2918178391" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer938899087365086957">[9/10]<br/><br/><b> Strangely enough, she always appeared on quiet rainy evenings. </b><br/><br/>Shimamoto – the one that got away, first love and first deception, an elusive ghost from the past that still haunts Hajime, a middle aged bar owner in a fashionable Tokyo district. I may be getting ahead of myself, as the present novel is not constructed around flashbacks, preferring instead a linear, chronological progression for Hajime, starting with his early school days and with his unlikely friendship with a quiet, but de</span>
  <span id="freeText938899087365086957" style="display:none">[9/10]<br /><br /><b> Strangely enough, she always appeared on quiet rainy evenings. </b><br /><br />Shimamoto – the one that got away, first love and first deception, an elusive ghost from the past that still haunts Hajime, a middle aged bar owner in a fashionable Tokyo district. I may be getting ahead of myself, as the present novel is not constructed around flashbacks, preferring instead a linear, chronological progression for Hajime, starting with his early school days and with his unlikely friendship with a quiet, but determinate girl.<br />My main reason for looking backward at the text is the musical connection, stronger here than in any other book by Murakami I’ve read so far. From the Nat King Cole inspired title to the often repeated refrain of Duke Ellington’s “Star Crossed Lovers” , I felt I was transported into one of those waking dreams that are Murakami’s signature touch. The bar room location, the movie-like dialogue, the mawkish sentimentality – all reinforced the impression of a jazz romance. But all of these come quite late in the novel. Before we get to them, we should meet Hajime properly.<br /><br /><i> It was merely the small, warm hand of a twelve-year-old girl, yet those five fingers and that palm were like a display case crammed full of everything I wanted to know – and everything I ‘had’to know. </i><br /><br />Born in the Japanese equivalent of a suburban home, to a middle class family like all the others on his street, Hajime sees himself as a special case in school because he is a single child at a time when everybody else had several siblings. I made note of his self-centered world-view, because it sort of defines Hajime at a key moment in his emotional and intelectual development. The boy’s chance at redemption comes from another single child, the crippled girl Shimamoto. The two kids are brought together by their common interest in books and music, as well as their oddball single child status. At twelve years old though, few kids are capable of self-awareness, much less of empathy. So Hajime and Shimamoto loose sight of one another when the boy moves to a different district for high school. In his later years, Hajime will have plenty of time to reconsider his actions.<br /><br /><b> I was afraid of rejection. I was still a child. I couldn’t imagine that you were actually waiting for me. I was terrified you would reject me. That I would come to your house to see you and you couldn’t be bothered. So I stopped coming. If I was going to get hurt, I thought it would be better to go on living with the happy memories of when we were together. </b><br /><br />But, like any other teenager ever, Hajime has plenty of new things to catch his interest. (Also, not surprisingly, these things are staples of Murakami novels, like cats, food, music and books)<br /><br /><b> I loved to read and to listen to music. I’d always liked books and reading, and my interest in these had been fostered by my friendship with Shimamoto. I started to go to the library, devouring every book I could lay my hands on. Once I began a book, I couldn’t put it down. It was like an addiction; I read while I ate, on the train, in bed until late at night, in school, where I’d keep the book hidden so I could read during class. </b><br /><br />Passages like this are one of the main reasons I was so attracted to the author when I first read him. That kind of behaviour describes exactly how I spent my four years of highschool, before shifting my main focus on grils. For Hajime, books and music are balanced by sports (swimming) and by a new romance: Izumi.<br /><br /><b> “I’m scared,” she said. “These days I feel like a snail without a shell.” </b><br /><br />Without getting into major sopilers, I think I will not surprise anybody when I mention that a young man driven by hormones and by an over-active imagination is not the most reliable of boyfriends. Exit Izumi, enters the third phase of our hero’s life story.<br /><br /><b> I consider this the third stage of my life – the twelve years between my starting college and turning thirty. Years of disappointment and loneliness. And silence. Frozen years, when my feelings were shut up inside me. </b><br /><br />Once again, Murakami pleasantly surprises me with how well he can transcend physical borders and cultural barriers in order to write about modern life, about dreams and depression, great expectations and crippling stress. Hajime discovers that as you age, making new friends is very difficult, having responsibilities and financial needs will force you into compromises and dead-end jobs.<br /><br /><i> No matter how you sliced it this wasn’t the job for me. I felt as if the end of my life was staring me in the face. The months and years would drop away one by one, with me bored out of my skull. I had thirty-three years till retirement, chained day after day to a desk, staring at galley proofs, counting lines, checking spelling. </i><br /><br />In a romantic novel that is curiously devoid of the usual weird stuff Murakami likes to include in his stories, the turning point between the third and the fourth age in the life of Hajime is marked by him seeing a ghost: that of a beautiful woman that looks a lot like his childhood friend Shimamoto. The ensuing pursuit through the streets of Tokyo is both fruitless and inconclusive: the woman remains a mystery. But Hajime will soon meet a new woman, Yukiko, he will get married and, with help from her rich father, start a new business. Not only will Hajime be his own boss, but he will have his dream job as the owner of a couple of jazz bars in a popular neighborhood.<br /><br /><b> “You are happy, aren’t you?” she asked.<br />“I don’t know. At least I’m not unhappy, and I’m not lonely.” A moment later, I added, “But sometimes the thought strikes me that the happiest time of my life was when we were together in your living room, listening to music.” </b><br /><br />Until this development, the novel was rather underwhelming, considering my usual expectations from the author. But musical bar owner happens to be one of my dream jobs, too, and it was very easy to put myself in Hajime’s shoes, especially when the mood turns definitely blue – in the song selections and in the slowly burning dialogues Hajime has with a mysteriously returned Shimamoto.<br /><br /><b> People are willing to spend a lot of money to come all this way to have some drinks – and do you know why? Because everyone’s seeking the same thing: an imaginary place, their own castle in the air, and their very own special corner of it. </b><br /><br />Music, literature, art in general, is our escape from a dreary reality, a way we still try to indulge in the dreams of our youth. Suddenly, the ordinary life of Hajime gains almost mythical signifiance. Murakami also shifts slighty away from the realist narration and engages in some low-level weirdness. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ The whole story of the return of Shimamoto might be only a waking dream of Hajime, who goes through his mid-life crisis despite having a loving wife and two beautiful daughters.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />The author finally manages to address the main obstacle I had in enjoying the romantic interludes between Hajime and the women in his life: basically, that he is a self-pitying jerk living in his own castle in the air and hurting the people who try to come close. He doesn’t deserve the reader’s sympathy:<br /><br /><b> You are definitely a selfish, hopeless person </b><br /><br />In conclusion, a typical Murakami novel that develops very slow but is redeemed by the ending. Very good use of music as a higher form of language. I will like to see it made into a movie, if it wasn’t already (have to check later). Nice touch at the end about dreamers and writers:<br /><br /><i> No one will weave dreams for me – it is my turn to weave dreams for others. That’s what I have to do. Such dreams may have no power, but if my own life is to have any meaning at all, that is what I have to do.<br />Probably. </i><br /><br />Recommended!<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="938899087365086957" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


