  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_352791212" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/352791212" />
    <a title="vivliovision" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5759755-vivliovision"><img alt="vivliovision" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1344926101p2/5759755.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/352791212?book_show_action=true">Jun 21, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="vivliovision" class="user" itemprop="url" name="vivliovision" href="/user/show/5759755-vivliovision">vivliovision</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer352791212" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14808561948737091553">keep in touch: <a target='_blank' rel='noopener nofollow' href='https://twitter.com/vivliovision'>https://twitter.com/vivliovision</a><br/><br/>Hajime is a happily married man. He is also the father of two daughters and the owner of two Jazz Clubs. At some point during his 30’s Hajime finds himself leading a typical suburban life close-enough-but-not-too-close to down-town Tokyo.<br/> <br/>Some people would say that Hajime is one of those lucky-few-guys, who can afford a rather easy-going lifestyle, while others would argue that this sort of life is quiet dull, actually. But then again, that&apos;s exactl</span>
  <span id="freeText14808561948737091553" style="display:none">keep in touch: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://twitter.com/vivliovision">https://twitter.com/vivliovision</a><br /><br />Hajime is a happily married man. He is also the father of two daughters and the owner of two Jazz Clubs. At some point during his 30’s Hajime finds himself leading a typical suburban life close-enough-but-not-too-close to down-town Tokyo.<br /> <br />Some people would say that Hajime is one of those lucky-few-guys, who can afford a rather easy-going lifestyle, while others would argue that this sort of life is quiet dull, actually. But then again, that's exactly how life is designed (or supposed) to be in the upper-middle-class suburbs of any post-modern metropolis, isn't it? Whatever the case might be, Hajime would probably agree with both points of view mentioned above. You see, he does consider himself part of a lucky-few-tribe; and yet, according to his own experience the members of this privileged-minority are not as carefree and happy-go-lucky as the majority think them to be.<br /><br />Besides, life hasn't always been a bowl of cherries for Hajime. "My four years of college", says he, "were pretty much a waste of time." Soon after graduation, he found himself a day-by-day job on the editorial staff of an educational publisher. His work there was as fascinating as it sounds. Nevertheless, Hajime stayed pinned down to that profession for eight long years. In short, his invaluable 20’s passed by in boredom, disappointment and loneliness. <br /><br />But, like the saying goes, nothing—either good or bad—is meant to last forever.<br /><br />Hajime meets Yukiko. According to him, "an irrational strong attraction pulled us together." Their affair is not exactly a romantic one; but still their feelings are sincere and their love is strong enough. Eventually, Yukiko ends-up grateful for her husband and Hajime seems also grateful for his wife. His father in law, president of a medium-sized construction company, is the one who makes sure that Yukiko’s and Hijime’s common life is going to be on the bright-site financially. Hajime’s father in law is first and foremost a practical man. He knows very well that money alone do not bring happiness to a family, but he is also perfectly aware that a happy family grows more easily in an environment of healthy prosperity. Thus, he gives Hajime all the assistance he needs -sometimes he's willing to give him much more than that- in order to do something for his family and himself. Hajime, able to do for a living what he would like to do anyway, very soon becomes a rather successful businessman. Here comes the first daughter. And here's the second one. Yukiko and Hajime’s marital life seems to run smoothly on some auto-pilot; just like some silky, old, jazz record. <br /><br />But once again, nothing –either bad or good– is meant to last forever. <br /><br />You see, Hajime’s got a thing for girls who have a small difficulty in walking. Shimamoto (a distant echo of Ulysses’ Gerty/Nausicca, perhaps?) happens to have the exact, slight deficiency that Hajime favours the most. Other than that, she is almost too perfect to be true. Moreover, Shimamoto in particular has a lot to do with Hajime's peculiar taste in women in general. In fact, their little story goes way back. At the beginning of the novel we learn that Shimamoto was Hajime’s first, tender love. <br /><br />Shimamoto, just like Hajime, was an only-child. That doesn't mean anything any more, but Shimamoto and Hajime grew up in a middle-class microcosm, where every typical family was supposed to have two kids. In this regard, they're both offspring of 'unusual' families. In a cruel world of immaturity, where anything that doesn't-look-exactly-alike gets simply marginalized, the two kids will inevitably become something like siblings to each other. Moreover, Shimamoto initiates Hajime to the multiversity of jazz. The two kids get along all right with each other. They walk to school together. They walk home from school together. They spend much of their free time together. They tell each other their clouded thoughts. And then, one fine day their paths drift apart. Their little, childish lives simply take different routes. Hajime keeps a rather fond memory of her father's record collection.<br /><br />Hajime feels sorry about the abrupt end of their little affair, but only in retrospect. In "real" time he didn't give it much thought. Besides, a short time afterwards another girl appears in Hajime’s life.<br /> <br />Izumi Ohara is a cute, young girl, who will be a mystery woman locked-up in some apartment, when she will grow up. Izumi is the girlfriend of Hajime’s adolescence. Hajime and Izumi like each other, but soon enough a familiar pattern will arise once again out the circumstances. This time Hajime wants to move to the big city. College-studies is pretty much an excuse for him. Izumi, on the other hand, neither does she want to follow Hajime’s road nor does she want a long-distance relationship. Their affair is heading to the rooks, apparently. Nevertheless Hajime wants to make love to Izumi. Izumi is not quite ready yet. Hajime sleeps with Izumi's cousin and he heads for Tokyo.<br /><br /><br />The rest is a fascinating story that can be read on Murakami’s novel. A novel that talks about the fragility of human feelings, the accompanying crisis of every transition from one stage of life to the next, the brief lapses of reason; and last but foremost, our difficulty to come in terms with our own mortality. Grown-ups know that real joy in life is rare, brief and hard to be found. Likewise, we know that the passion of (unfulfilled or unfortunate) love can occasionally grow so wild that may lead reason to suspense and us to all wrong decisions. And above all else, sooner or later we all come to realise eventually that death and love are the opposite sides of the very same coin, indeed. <br /><br />This hard-gained knowledge doesn't make the acceptance process much easier. And yet, there's some sort of comfort to be found on the road to nowhere. Although this world can really look like a honky-tonk parade on occasions, we're all in this parade together. This bitter-and-sweet, harsh-and-tender, with-and-without life is our common reality. <br /><br />PS I : To my understanding "South of the Border, West of the Sun" is the prequel of Murakami's "Norwegian Wood", which had been written five years earlier.<br /><br />PS II: There are barely any cats in this story. </span>
  <a data-text-id="14808561948737091553" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


