  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2547198042" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2547198042" />
    <a title="Cody" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4886576-cody"><img alt="Cody" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1551053892p2/4886576.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2547198042?book_show_action=true">Sep 30, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cody" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cody" href="/user/show/4886576-cody">Cody</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780679767398" href="/book/show/33263.South_of_the_Border_West_of_the_Sun">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4886576-cody?shelf=haruki-murakami">haruki-murakami</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2547198042" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7862475532365498219">&quot;Because everyone&apos;s seeking the same thing: an imaginary place, their own castle in the air, and their very own special corner of it.&quot; (105)<br/><br/>South of the Border, West of the Sun is a representation of classical Haruki Murakami lore. Murakami traces the life of Hajime, a man born of a relatively peaceful post-WWII life where, rather than the traditional struggles of poverty, war, famine, or religious identity, his struggles come from his own sense of purpose and meaning. And of course being Muraka</span>
  <span id="freeText7862475532365498219" style="display:none">"Because everyone's seeking the same thing: an imaginary place, their own castle in the air, and their very own special corner of it." (105)<br /><br />South of the Border, West of the Sun is a representation of classical Haruki Murakami lore. Murakami traces the life of Hajime, a man born of a relatively peaceful post-WWII life where, rather than the traditional struggles of poverty, war, famine, or religious identity, his struggles come from his own sense of purpose and meaning. And of course being Murakami, there's all the tropes associated with him: cats, jazz music, blowjobs, and that aching sense of loneliness.<br /><br />Reading South of the Border, West of the Sun was reminiscent of another book about the idea of identity crisis in a time and culture where a person has everything yet seemingly feels helpless and numb: Fight Club. "We're the middle children of the history man, no purpose or place, we have no Great war, no Great depression, our great war is a spiritual war, our great depression is our lives." While the two books differ in some respects, they both question the need of material possessions and social fulfilment. Hajime ends of owning two Jazz bars, is successful in business making good money, marries and has two daughters, and drives a nice BMW. And yet, the existence of a lack of fulfilment compounds his thoughts so much he begins to suffer for it. "What am I missing," he continually asks himself. This lack of fulfilment answers itself in the form of his first ever love, Shimamoto, a woman so mysterious she pops in and out of Hajime's life, haunting him. Diving into this aspect will spoil a few things, but it is important to note Shimamoto's role is multilayered and debatable.<br /><br />The book consistently makes reference to a film The Living Desert. "All that remains is a desert." Desert as a word can invoke the image of something like the Sahara: a barrenness wasteland of little meaning. However the desert depicted in the film is one in the American Southwest. A land full of life. Hajime associates a more negative image of a desert to his life, when in reality his life mirrors the American Southwest in that it's full of life and significant micro-transactions that give it so much more meaning than he can imagine. By the end of the book he comes to this realisation and hopes to build on it. That encompasses the theme of this book. How can we make meaning of what's in front of us rather than letting our "imaginary castles" drag us down into a depression we don't deserve nor need. This theme makes it one of the better books written by Murakami.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7862475532365498219" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

